# NOTE: Keep this list short (~8 entries). Remove old ones as new ones land.
CHANGELOG = [
    "b430: the spellcasting roster goes wide + the casters get a real toolkit. b429's playtest showed the spell engine barely surfaced -- only the base Lich cast, and it's rare, so the deep liches you actually fight (Dragon Lich, Hollow/Necrarch/Sepulchral/Nightmare Lich) just swung. Now 24 monsters across every tier carry spell lists: all the liches (necrotic bolts + self-heals), the psionic line (Mind Flayer/Illithid Overmind/Elder Brain mind-blast + a Dominate stun), the genies & fiends (Efreeti/Djinn/Warlord/Demilich/Night Hag/Succubus elemental bolts, drains, and heals). Two new spell mechanics back the marquee casters: self_buff spells (a monster wards ITSELF -- Monster.take_damage now honors hit_absorb, so a Lich's Force Shield eats a couple of blows) and spell_ward (a Rakshasa's Spell Turning counters your NEXT spell -- checked in Character.cast_spell). The Beholder is the showpiece: a five-ray menu (Disintegration / Antimagic-silence / Petrification-stun / Slowing / Enervation) picked at random each turn, so no two rounds look alike. Deep bolts bypass armor but sit well under the monster's brutal melee, so they read as variety, not a difficulty spike.",
    "b429: caster monsters now actually CAST SPELLS. Until now even the bestiary's wizards just swung melee with an on-hit status rider -- a Lich named for being an undead archmage hit you with a stick. New monster-spellcasting layer: a caster carries a 'spells' list + a per-turn 'spell_chance', and Monster._try_cast_spell() (called at the top of attack_target) may cast a spell INSTEAD of swinging -- alternative damage, not bonus. Three spell types: damage (routes through take_damage so it BYPASSES armor like the player's own spells, but still respects elemental resistance / Stone Skin / Spectral Hand), heal (the monster mends itself, preferred when below 50% HP), and debuff (applies a status via the existing effect machinery). First wave of casters: Lich (Necrotic Bolt + a Drain Vitality self-heal), Sphinx (Word of Power), Rakshasa (Mind Twist + a Phantom Veil that blinds you), and the bug-level Firefly Mage (Lumen Lance) + Dragonfly Enchantress (Prismatic Bolt + an enervating weakness charm). Spells pass through at both the normal and bug-monster spawn sites; non-casters are unaffected. The roster is data-driven, so widening it to the deep liches/fiends later is just more 'spells' entries.",
    "b428: monsters fight like the monsters they're supposed to be. A huge swath of the bestiary had special_attack entries that were pure flavor -- the log bragged about a Lich's necromantic blast or a Kraken's crushing coils, but mechanically NOTHING happened, because the effect types weakness/slow/curse (and a 'drain' typo on the Dragon Lich) were never wired into combat. Now they bite: weakness saps the player's effective attack by its magnitude (Character.attack), curse/defense_penalty pry your guard open by reducing defense (Character.defense), slow gives a 30% chance each turn that your sluggish action fizzles while the monster strikes freely, and Dragon Lich's drain is now real life_drain. That alone turns ~30 cosmetic specials into genuine threats (Lich, Beholder, Rakshasa, Mummy, Tarrasque, Basilisk, Kraken, the deep liches, ...). Both attack/defense clamp at >=0. Also: monster passive regeneration (new 'regen' template field, fraction of max HP/turn) -- the Troll now knits its wounds each turn (burn it down or stalemate). And ~11 formerly-vanilla bruisers got thematic specials: Owlbear/Griffin/Bulette bleed, Minotaur/Roc/Cyclops gore-stun, Hill Giants daze (weakness), Stone Golem slam (slow), Frost Giant freeze, Crawling Claw clinging grip (sticky_hands), Displacer Beasts blur your aim (blindness). Pure low-tier fodder (goblins, kobolds, orcs, gnolls, bats) stays honest melee.",
    "b427: tiered ENTRANCE flourishes -- the stronger the foe, the bigger the reveal. Each tier carries a flourish level (0-4) that plays a scaled entrance on the monster sprite (the loom overlay when looming, else the in-flow canvas), rising from bottom-center: DANGEROUS/DEADLY = pop (1), CHAMPION = rise (2), LEGENDARY = surge + a soft haptic buzz (3), BOSS = a dramatic SLAM + full-screen red flash + a building vibration pattern (4). It fires ONCE per fight, not every turn: _combat_anim_token() bumps a token when a new monster appears and the JS gates on window.__combatAnimTok, so re-renders stay static. Vibration uses navigator.vibrate (Android webview; iOS WKWebView silently no-ops). New flourish field on get_monster_threat_style() + flourishPop/Rise/Surge/Slam keyframes; generate_monster_sprite_html() gained flourish + anim_token params.",
    "b426: elite sprites now loom as a JS overlay OVER the HUD, and the map is nailed in place. Instead of fighting #content-area's clip with CSS margins (which moved the map), the oversized boss/legendary sprite is mounted as a fixed-position canvas on a top layer (class loom-overlay, z-index 1200) -- the same trick as the spell/damage effects -- so it paints right over the stats bar. Being out of document flow, it can't move anything: HARD RULE met, the map sits exactly where a normal fight puts it at every tier. Freed from the box, bosses grew to 150px (was 118) and legendaries to 120px. generate_monster_sprite_html() gained a loom flag that clones the sprite into the overlay on load; updateGame() clears .loom-overlay on every re-render so nothing lingers between screens (victory caps the sprite at 96px and skips the overlay so the defeat grayscale stays clean). Also: when a sprite is big, the monster name/HP text pins to the TOP of the box (align-items:flex-start) so the roll dice have clear room below.",
    "b425: bottom-anchor the loom so elite fights stop shoving the map down. b424 made room for the looming boss sprite by adding margin-top to the whole .room-panel -- which pushed the map (and chips/log) down by the full loom (44px boss / 16px legendary). But the fixed 200px panel already had ~30px of unused space below the player box. Now the combat panels are bottom-anchored (flex justify-content:flex-end) so that dead space sits at the TOP, and the sprite looms up into it; only the sliver that still pokes past the panel needs margin headroom. Net: LEGENDARY now shifts the map 0px (fits entirely in the reclaimed gap), BOSS only 9px (was 44px). Sprites stay exactly as big. get_monster_threat_style() now derives the residual headroom from the panel budget and returns roompanel_loom_css (fixed-200px combat/flee/victory) + growbox_loom_css (the spell view, which has no map and just grows/scrolls).",
    "b424: elite monsters now LOOM over their battle box instead of clipping your own panel. The combat view packs the monster + player boxes into a fixed 200px slot (.room-panel, overflow:hidden), so the b423 boss sprite (118px) was overflowing ~10px and cutting off the bottom of the player's HP/MP/stats box. Fix: for the rare elite tiers the monster sprite is bottom-anchored in a height-capped flow slot (sprite_size - loom_px) and spills UPWARD; the four combat render sites give the container a matching margin-top + overflow:visible so the creature towers up into headroom (right to the #content-area ceiling) rather than eating the budget below it. loom_px is 0 for common fights (no map shift, no jitter), 16px for LEGENDARY, 44px for BOSS -- so only the dramatic encounters nudge the map down a touch, which reads as the boss dominating the screen. New wrap_monster_loom() + loom_px/slot_css/panel_loom_css fields on get_monster_threat_style(); player box stays safely inside 200px at every tier.",
    "b423: combat displays now scale with difficulty. The monster battle box reads its threat at a glance: weak foes shrink (50px sprite, muted gray box), even fights stay normal (64px), and tougher monsters grow bigger sprites with fiercer, glowing boxes -- TOUGH (74px, orange), DANGEROUS (84px, pulsing red-orange), DEADLY (92px, pulsing red). Threat is relative to player level (monster.level - player.level), so the same goblin looks trivial late-game and the box telegraphs when you're outclassed. Special monsters override the relative scale with signature looks: CHAMPION (96px, gold pulse), LEGENDARY (104px, purple pulse, badge), and BOSS -- Zot's Guardian, Platino, the Bug Queen -- (118px, thick red border, fastest gold-red pulse, BOSS badge). New get_monster_threat_style() in app.py drives all four combat render paths (combat, spell-casting, fleeing, victory) plus a size param on generate_monster_sprite_html(); a single threatPulse keyframe serves every tier via a --tg CSS var carrying the per-tier glow color. The victory/defeat view reuses the fight's styling so a slain boss keeps its menacing frame as it greys out.",
]

